╭─ Assistant [MainThread@3555170] ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ The `CreateShuffleVector` function in `IRBuilderBase` has multiple overloads. The one that introduces a `poison` value as the second operand is defined as:                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                                            │
│ Value *CreateShuffleVector(Value *V, ArrayRef<int> Mask, const Twine &Name = "") {                                                                                                                                │
│   return CreateShuffleVector(V, PoisonValue::get(V->getType()), Mask, Name);                                                                                                                                      │
│ }                                                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ This function calls another overload of `CreateShuffleVector`:                                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                                            │
│ Value *CreateShuffleVector(Value *V1, Value *V2, ArrayRef<int> Mask, const Twine &Name = "") {                                                                                                                    │
│   if (Value *V = Folder.FoldShuffleVector(V1, V2, Mask))                                                                                                                                                          │
│     return V;                                                                                                                                                                                                     │
│   return Insert(new ShuffleVectorInst(V1, V2, Mask), Name);                                                                                                                                                       │
│ }                                                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ The issue likely arises when the `poison` value is used as the second operand (`V2`) in the shuffle vector instruction. This can lead to the introduction of `poison` values in the resulting vector, as          │
│ described in the bug report.                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ To address this, we need to modify the `CreateShuffleVector` function to ensure that the `poison` value does not propagate into the resulting vector. This can be achieved by validating the shuffle mask and     │
│ ensuring that it does not reference elements from the `poison` operand.                                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ I will now propose and implement a fix for this issue.                                                                                                                                                            │
